t283.text: Its scientific name translates to ‘horned keeper of the forest’. At least 131 of 860 Australia’s reptile species are found in the Wet Tropics.

t284.text: When threatened, the northern leaf-tailed gecko raises and wags its tail from side to side to draw attention away from the head—it can shed its tail as a decoy if attacked. It is also known to open its mouth and charge aggressors while vocalizing.

t285.text: Living in the cool moist conditions of the Wet Tropics, its camouflage coloration looks like the lichen-mottled bark it lives on.

t286.text: This is the northern leaf-tailed gecko (Saltuarius cornutus). A nocturnal, tree-dwelling gecko, it has an unusual triangular head and an 8cm broad, leaf-like tail. With an overall size up to 14cm, the northern leaf-tailed gecko is one of Australia’s largest geckos.
